// Section 05 — Listening
#import "../utils.typ": divider, dingbat-line, section-heading, pullquote, pullquote-display, section-opener, callout

#section-heading("V", "Listening")

#section-opener[
A friend tells you something hard. Their dog died, or their boss humiliated them, or the thing they have been afraid of for six months turned out to be true. You open your mouth.
]

What comes out, if you are like most well-meaning humans, is one of three things.

_The explanation._ _Well, the reason that probably happened is..._ You are about to deliver a small theory of why their pain occurred, complete with reasonable people on both sides. The friend, in this moment, did not need a theory. The friend needed someone to be in the room with them.

_The recentering._ _Oh my god, that reminds me of when my boss did exactly the same thing to me last year, it was so awful..._ You meant well. You were trying to say _me too._ What you said, in effect, was _let me have your microphone for a moment._ You took the conversation back to yourself. The friend, watching, has now learned that this is not a place where their thing can stay the center of the room for very long.

_The fix._ _Have you tried..._ Maybe they have. Maybe they haven't. Either way, what they were asking for, in this moment, was probably not a list of things to try. They were asking to feel less alone for two minutes. The fix-it response says: _I cannot stay with this with you. Let me hand you something to do so I can leave._

These are the three classical failure modes of well-meant listening. They are committed by kind people, all the time, including the author, including you. They are not malice. They are mostly the listener's own discomfort looking for somewhere to put itself.

All three miss the same thing: they move the conversation away from the feeling before it has been met.

#divider

*What empathy actually is.*

#callout[Empathy, in NVC's working definition, is the orientation toward the other person's feelings and needs — the willingness to stay there without needing to solve, redirect, fix, or take it back to yourself.]

Empathy is not silence. Empathy is not agreement. Empathy is not problem-solving. Empathy is not nodding while you wait to talk.

Empathy, in NVC's working definition, is the orientation toward the other person's feelings and needs — the willingness to stay there, with them, without needing to solve, redirect, fix, or take it back to yourself. It might involve speech. It might not. The form of empathy is downstream of its orientation.

What it sounds like, in actual words, is often: _something like — are you hurt? are you scared? are you exhausted? do you need to feel like this matters to someone right now?_ You are not asking because you don't know. You are asking because the asking is the act of staying — the offer to follow them into the actual feeling instead of pulling them out of it.

Sarah Peyton, the trauma-informed NVC trainer, makes the most useful point in the field on this: _being warmly and accurately misread is more healing than being correctly understood without warmth._ Read that sentence twice. It collapses the entire NVC-purist anxiety about whether you guessed the feeling right.

#pullquote[The brain is built for resonance, not correctness.]

Get within striking distance of what they are feeling, with warmth, and the body responds. Get the exact right word with no warmth and the body does not.

This means you are allowed to guess wrong. You are _supposed_ to guess wrong, sometimes. The friend will correct you — _no, not exhausted, more like furious_ — and now you are both closer to the actual thing than you were a minute ago. Your wrong guess made theirs findable.

#divider

*Empathy as co-regulation.*

If you are willing to follow the wire all the way, empathic listening is doing something more specific than _being supportive._ A body in distress is a body running its threat response — wired hot, or gone numb, neither a state in which words come easily. Another body, regulated and present, offers something the upset body cannot manufacture alone: cues of safety. Slow voice. Soft eyes. Steady breath. Unhurried timing. The presence of someone whose nervous system is saying, without words, _we are not in danger right now._

Empathic listening, done well, is co-regulation with words. A body in distress is scanning the room for cues of threat or safety — _neuroception_, the trauma writers call it — and the regulated body in the room is the cue of safety, prior to and underneath whatever specific phrasing comes out. Half the work is happening in the room before anyone has chosen the right adjective.

It is also why an empathic listener whose own body is dysregulated — anxious, judgmental, in a hurry, performing helpfulness — will not produce the effect, no matter how technically correct their sentences are. The dead-eyed therapist demo voice you can hear in any badly-trained role-play is exactly this. Words, no body. Form, no orientation. The trap with extra steps, again.

*Asymmetric use.*

#callout[You do not need the other person to be doing NVC for you to listen with it. The practice does not require their cooperation.]

One of the more useful things about NVC, and one of the most rarely emphasized in the workshops, is that you do not need the other person to be doing it for you to listen with it.

Your stepfather, in full sympathetic activation, telling you for the seventh year running that your generation has ruined this country: he is, by inspection, not using NVC. You are not required to fix that. You can listen with NVC anyway. From the inside, what that looks like is tracking the feeling underneath the rant — probably some mixture of fear, helplessness, grief about a world that no longer makes sense to him, pride that has been bruised — and the need underneath the feeling, probably to matter, to be seen as having lived a life that meant something, to feel like the things he believed in still exist somewhere. You don't have to agree with any of it. You don't have to say any of it out loud. You can. You can also just be present and not bait the trap. The asymmetric move is internal — what you are doing inside yourself while he is talking. You are refusing to be recruited. You are keeping your own interior alive while his is running hot. You are not escalating, not baiting, not collapsing into the performance of agreement. That is not passivity. That is a specific choice about what to do with your nervous system in a room where nobody asked for your cooperation. And it does, weirdly, change the room. Sometimes.

This is also where listening becomes a small political practice. You can listen with NVC to people who do not deserve it by their own behavior. You can listen with NVC to people whose worldview you find repugnant. Whether you _should_, in any given case, is a separate question. Protecting your own nervous system is a real concern, especially across asymmetric power dynamics, and the answer is sometimes _no, not tonight, not this person, not in this body._ But the practice does not require their cooperation. Naming this matters because the workshop pedagogy almost never does.

#divider

*The numb friend.*

A note for the moments when your friend's honest answer is _I don't know what I feel._

Most NVC pedagogy assumes the speaker can locate a feeling. Trauma-informed NVC has decent material for someone in sympathetic activation; it has less for someone in dorsal-vagal shutdown — the friend who has gone numb, or underwater, or who is functionally underneath the conversation.

The work, when this is what is in the room, is not to push for words. It is to be present without demand. Not to require them to produce a feeling you can then empathically reflect. Sometimes that means sitting with them. Sometimes it means making them tea. Sometimes it means going for a walk and not talking. Resmaa Menakem and the somatic trauma writers will tell you, in stronger language than this booklet has space for, that words applied to a body that has not yet decided it is safe can re-traumatize. The empathic move, in that state, is body-first. Words later. Sometimes much later.

NVC as packaged often assumes a body that hasn't been racialized into chronic survival mode. A feelings-and-needs script in that context can ask someone to perform emotional disclosure in a format shaped by white middle-class norms — in the same moment their anger or numbness is the most accurate information in the room. Roxy Manning, Edmundo Norte, and Meenadchi have spent years doing the work of retooling the practice for bodies it wasn't originally designed for. That is where to go next.

